  <h1>SheetAlchemy Privacy Policy</h1>
  <h2 style="font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 400; color: var(--color-text-secondary); margin-top: 0;">Python Library for Google Sheets</h2>
  <p style="color: var(--color-text-secondary); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: var(--spacing-lg);">Last Updated: December 2025</p>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    SheetAlchemy is a Python library that provides a programmatic interface for interacting with Google Sheets. 
    It allows developers to read, write, and manage spreadsheets through code.
  </p>

  <h2>Information Collected</h2>
  <p style="padding: var(--spacing-md); background: var(--color-border); margin: var(--spacing-md) 0;">
    <strong>SheetAlchemy does not collect or store any user data.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    SheetAlchemy is a library that runs entirely on your machine. It does not transmit telemetry, 
    usage data, or any information to external servers.
  </p>

  <h2>Data Handling</h2>
  <p>
    If you configure Google API keys, OAuth tokens, or sheet data, it stays:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>In your user code</li>
    <li>On your infrastructure</li>
    <li>Under your control</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>No External Logging</h2>
  <p>
    The library performs no external logging, telemetry, or transmission of any kind. 
    All operations are local to your Python environment.
  </p>

  <h2>Third-Party Services</h2>
  <p>
    SheetAlchemy communicates with Google Sheets APIs when you explicitly call it. 
    Refer to <a href="https://policies.google.com/privacy" target="_blank">Google's Privacy Policy</a> 
    for information about how Google handles data sent through their APIs.
  </p>

  <h2>Google Authentication</h2>
  <p>
    When you use OAuth authentication with Google, you control:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Which credentials are used</li>
    <li>What permissions you grant</li>
    <li>Which sheets you connect to</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    SheetAlchemy never stores or transmits your credentials to any third party.
  </p>

